{"title":"Parallel Structures in Pre-training Data Yield In-Context Learning","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"It is unclear which patterns in natural pre-training text give rise to language models’ in-context learning (ICL) despite the distribution shift between natural text and in-context prompts.","method":"Introduce and formalize parallel structures (PS): pairs of phrases within the same context window that follow the same underlying distribution. Propose a gradient-based PS-strength detector: take a pretrained LM, perform one gradient step on a former phrase (context, token), and measure log-likelihood improvement on a latter phrase; larger improvement implies stronger PS (Sec. 3.2). Make the detector scalable by (i) restricting latter phrases to short, overlapping segments and (ii) minibatching former phrases, achieving strong correlation with the exact per-phrase update (+0.71 Pearson; m=12, l=128, η=1e-4)."},{"problem":"Whether parallel structures causally drive ICL remains unverified on real pre-training data.","method":"Causally test PS by ablating them in pre-training data: replace the last token of each detected latter phrase with a random token, then continue pre-train GPT-2 Small–XL on OpenWebText and evaluate ICL on 9 tasks with 64–128 shots. Removing PS causes a large average ICL drop (51.1% relative) versus random ablation (1.5%), consistent across model sizes, while fine-tuning accuracy remains comparable to random ablation, indicating the loss is specifically in ICL ability (Tables 2–3, Sec. 6.1)."},{"problem":"It is unknown if PS effects are merely due to n-gram repetitions or generic long-range dependencies.","method":"Disentangle via controlled ablations: (a) Exclude n-gram repetitions when scoring PS (-PS+Rp); ablating these non-repetition PS still yields a 37.9% average ICL drop and notably hurts copy (81.8% relative drop), showing PS beyond copying are critical (Sec. 6.2). (b) Ablate long-range dependencies not explained by PS (-Dp+PS); this yields a smaller 17.5% average drop versus 51.1% for PS, demonstrating PS have a larger causal effect on ICL than generic long-range dependency (Sec. 6.2)."}]}
